ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the selectivity of N-CDs/Fe3+ towards GSH, interference assays were also analyzed with 8 amino acids, including main competitive reduced amino acid Cys under identical condition. Before testing, 1 mL determined amino acid (10−2 M) was separately dispersed in 2 mL N-CDs/Fe3+ (v:v = 2:3) to form homogenous solution. After that, fluorescence recovery (I/I0) degrees were measured to analyze the selectivity of N-CDs/Fe3+ in the presence of interference amino acids (Fig. 3
                        a). Obviously, N-CDs/Fe3+ exhibited higher fluorescence recovery with GSH than other amino acids, suggesting that N-CDs/Fe3+ had high selectivity towards GSH and can be applied for GSH detection. Meanwhile, the quenched fluorescence emission gradually recovered with increasing concentration of reduced GSH, which implied that the “turn off” part was broken for Fe3+ was reduced to Fe2+ by GSH with redox reaction, inducing fluorescence partly recovery (Fig. 3b). Furthermore, the calibration curve for N-CDs/Fe3+ towards GSH exhibited a linear relationship in the range from 0 μM to 67 μM, and the corresponding LoD was 0.226 μM (Fig. S2b). On the basis of the above findings, N-CDs/Fe3+/GSH could be developed as an effective fluorescence “on–off–on” sensor for GSH detection rather than most of the reported methods (Table 2
                        ).
